&amp;quot;Domain wall motion in thin ferromagnetic nanotubes: Analytic results&amp;quot;, A. Goussev, J. M. Robbins, V. Slastikov, EPL (Europhys. Lett.) 105, 67006 (2014)</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5461dae3eadc00.33085019-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Contributed with research expertise and intellectual input.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>Contributed with research expertise and intellectual input.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>A domain wall is an interface separating magnetic domains. Domain walls can be set in motion by application of external magnetic fields or electric currents. The field and current control of domain wall motion has been proposed as a basis for next generation memory devices in which domain walls are used for the information storage.

We have found addressed domain wall dynamics in thin ferromagnetic nanotubes with and without spin-orbit-induced Dzyaloshinskii-Moriya interaction, and found, for the first time, exact analytical solutions for the domain wall profiles and explicit formulas for the propagation velocity.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our analytical results may be used in guiding further numerical simulations of ferromagnetic nanostructures and designing future magnetic memory devices.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>FB44CD0D-4F82-46EC-959F-1A71F9256716</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5461e234c635c2.73521965</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Electronics,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>B76F52AE-78F1-4AC5-8B42-45BF3811A022</gtr:id><gtr:title>Towards a quantum time mirror for nonrelativistic wave packets</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>New Journal of Physics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/ec8a99eff084fceafacc68836399ea4a"><gtr:id>ec8a99eff084fceafacc68836399ea4a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Reck P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2018-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>5a9959e43c23f6.90656224</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>D1E05133-A3E0-4F08-8747-3965E37C62A9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Origin of the exponential decay of the Loschmidt echo in integrable systems.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Physical review. E, Statistical, nonlinear, and soft matter physics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/3c0dbe5e1d532c8ab8390ee3479b0db1"><gtr:id>3c0dbe5e1d532c8ab8390ee3479b0db1</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Dubertrand R</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></